---------

On the eve of tomorrow=E2=80=99s House speaker vote, all eyes are on Texas
Rep. Chip Roy, an inveterate budget hawk and occasional iconoclast, as the =
canary in the coalmine for any effort to depose Mike Johnson. With a razor-=
thin margin, and Kentucky Rep. Thomas Massie already saying he=E2=80=99s vo=
ting against him, Johnson can afford to lose only one other House Republica=
n if he wants to hold on to the gavel.

There are other potential nays, of course, but the
conventional wisdom on the Hill is that if Roy votes against Johnson, the d=
am probably breaks. It=E2=80=99s a pickle for Johnson because, while Roy is=
 about as conservative as it gets in the House=E2=80=94and Johnson, himself=
, was long viewed as a fellow ideologue=E2=80=94he is not a reliable vote f=
or leadership. And it doesn=E2=80=99t help that Johnson has pushed a number=
 of hard votes over the past year, occasionally leaning on Democrats (and p=
issing off the likes of Marjorie Taylor Greene, Andy
Biggs, Paul Gosar, Massie, and others) to keep the government funded and se=
nd aid to Ukraine. Like a growing bloc of House Republicans, Roy is a contr=
arian=E2=80=94but not purely one of the attention-seeking variety. When he =
takes a position, he=E2=80=99s usually uncompromisingly sincere about it, a=
nd that makes him potentially more difficult to talk back into the fold. (W=
hile Democrats may loathe his views, privately they admire his consistency.=
)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, Trump has been calling around to help shore up support for Johns=
on, and has implied that he would back primary challenges against members w=
ho don=E2=80=99t fall in line. But Trump has already called ( https://www.t=
exastribune.org/2024/12/19/donald-trump-chip-roy-debt-ceiling/?utm_campaign=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3D=
The+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demai=
l_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) for someb=
ody to primary Roy, and he can=E2=80=99t play the same card
twice. Roy=E2=80=99s district is super Trumpy=E2=80=94a rare patch of deep =
red near Austin, where the Texas Republican political class of operatives a=
nd Hill Country state representatives are concentrated. As such, there=E2=
=80=99s an ample supply of potential opponents=E2=80=94every wannabe Republ=
ican congressmember in the greater Austin metropolitan region ran for the s=
eat when Roy first did in 2018.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But Roy defeated
17 other Republicans in that race. He=E2=80=99s got a killer team on speed =
dial that includes several of the Austin-based strategists who plotted Ted =
Cruz=E2=80=99s upset victory over the establishment in 2012. And again, he =
already incurred Trump=E2=80=99s wrath for loudly voting against the Trump-=
 and Johnson-backed bill to keep the government open in December. Indeed, R=
oy has cited ( https://www.foxnews.com/video/6366615811112?utm_campaign=3DT=
he+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+=
Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_ac=
tion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
that very legislation, and its $300 billion in additional deficit spending,=
 as a reason he=E2=80=99s skeptical of Johnson.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Sure, the political world could look entirely different in 2026, but for no=
w, Roy is in as strong shape as any other incumbent to survive a primary=E2=
=80=94and thus, among the least swayable by a Trump endorsement or threat. =
Which is bad news for Johnson as Friday=E2=80=99s vote looms.

And now to the main event=E2=80=A6

