*******************

A hard and honest conversation with presidential historian Douglas
Brinkley about the strange end of the Biden era, how his legacy will be mea=
sured against his successor=E2=80=99s, and whether history will redeem him.

Tara Palmeri ( https://puck.news/author/tara-palmeri/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Be=
st+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+=
%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Tara Palmeri ( https://puck.news/author/tara-palmeri/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Be=
st+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+=
%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

In Washington, emotions are still raw over outgoing President
Joe Biden: Democrats are angry that he opted to run for reelection after im=
plying he=E2=80=99d be a =E2=80=9Cbridge=E2=80=9D president; frustrated he =
took so long to drop out after the debate; rageful over down-ballot losses =
they attribute to his ego; and disillusioned by his decision to pardon Hunt=
er after insisting he wouldn=E2=80=99t. This was the guy who promised to de=
fend democracy from Donald Trump, and yet he shares no small part of the bl=
ame for Trump=E2=80=99s return to the
White House.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Biden, who was elected in part because voters were sick of chaos and wanted=
 to think less about politics, is leaving office quietly, at 82 years old, =
with a 37 percent approval rating, while his successor is already negotiati=
ng with foreign leaders over tariffs and immigration. Meanwhile, some of Bi=
den=E2=80=99s team are struggling to find donors for his presidential libra=
ry, and others
are leaking to the press about the administration=E2=80=99s depressing fina=
l days.

=C2=A0

Still, Biden has had a remarkable 50-year career, despite its anticlimactic=
 end, which makes for a long story to tell. Will Biden be remembered for he=
lping pass a major infrastructure package, restoring normalcy after the pan=
demic, his investments in semiconductor manufacturing, and combating climat=
e change? Or will history remember the botched
Afghanistan withdrawal, high inflation, and the border crisis? I spoke to t=
he presidential historian Douglas Brinkley on my podcast, Somebody=E2=80=99=
s Gotta Win ( https://puck.news/podcast_episode/how-history-will-judge-joe-=
biden-with-presidential-historian-doug-brinkley/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%2=
6+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+T=
he+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_s=
ource=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), about these and other =
stimulating questions. The following is a lightly edited excerpt from our c=
onversation.=C2=A0

Post-Debate Revisionism
-----------------------

Tara Palmeri: The presidency has
been a strange capstone to Biden=E2=80=99s 50-year legacy in Washington. Th=
e fact that he was pushed by his own party to abandon his reelection campai=
gn is obviously something that will be remembered by history, as will his d=
ecision to pardon Hunter. Do you think those black marks will overshadow hi=
s accomplishments?

=C2=A0

Douglas Brinkley: The good news for Joe Biden is we tend to do an upward
revision when somebody leaves office. So when you=E2=80=99re looking at Joe=
 Biden=E2=80=99s large career, people will find some nuggets of legislative=
 success and his knowledge on international affairs. Of course, Biden has a=
 different view of what=E2=80=99s happened this past year than historians, =
journalists, and other commentators. This is the Biden view of it: He was d=
oing swimmingly well; he knew how to beat Trump; yes, he screwed up in the =
debate, but he should have hung in there and could have won, because he
was the secret key to the white working class of Pennsylvania, Michigan, Wi=
sconsin, and those key states. And alas, there was a revolt in his own part=
y. And that challenge came from Nancy Pelosi and Chuck Schumer, with a nod =
of support from the Obama team, in a way.

=C2=A0

As soon as that happened, Biden=E2=80=99s legacy was going to be determined=
 on
whether Kamala Harris won. One scenario would have been, Biden blew the deb=
ate, but he=E2=80=99s such a nice man and he had all the electoral delegate=
s, but he gave them to Kamala Harris and she becomes the first woman presid=
ent in U.S. history. In this case, we would be looking at an inaugural wher=
e Biden is lionized. The other scenario was what happened=E2=80=94Donald Tr=
ump wins, and with Trump winning, the big loser becomes Biden. Trumpism is =
alive and well, MAGA
world is alive and well, and Biden is being talked about alongside =E2=80=
=9Ccognitive decline=E2=80=9D and screwing up the Democratic Party and caus=
ing a leadership void. His legacy was tied to the election, and it didn=E2=
=80=99t turn out well.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Pelosi and Schumer pushed him out, but he was severely lagging behind Trump=
 after the debate. He had a 36 percent approval rating, about where he=E2=
=80=99s hovering now. Arguably,
Biden stepping down was the only way to save the party. But many Democrats =
say he waited too long=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s what dragged them down.

=C2=A0

After the debate debacle between Trump and Biden, I was on MSNBC the next m=
orning, and I said Biden=E2=80=99s gotta step down from office now, and han=
d over the presidency to Kamala Harris. He would have been in better shape,=
 because he would have then allowed Harris to be running as the sitting
president of the United States, would have allowed her to go on European tr=
ips, and do things as the sitting president. In the worst-case scenario, Bi=
den would be remembered for giving America our first woman president. That =
would have been a big plus to his legacy. Biden was just flat in 2024, and =
he=E2=80=99s leaving office as a flat tire.

Weekend at Biden=E2=80=99s
--------------------

Do you think his legacy will be that we had a
non-functional president for the final year, and that Jill Biden was the on=
e running the show, like Nancy Reagan?

=C2=A0

In Biden=E2=80=99s case, after year two, there was no there there, it seeme=
d. Anybody meeting Joe Biden knew that this was an issue. We really need to=
 know who was in the inner circle in the White House, who was trying to pro=
tect him like that. You started seeing the Biden circle
trying to beat up on the press like CNN, MSNBC, The New York Times, The Was=
hington Post=E2=80=94which, by and large, offered fairly positive coverage=
=E2=80=94and demonizing them, as if they=E2=80=99re the problem. Biden had =
a career where he talked to the press=E2=80=94the press liked him=E2=80=94a=
nd suddenly his aides started going after every reporter they=E2=80=99d see=
 on TV saying Biden might be too old.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As for what Biden
will be remembered for=E2=80=A6 I think the Inflation Reduction Act was epi=
c, but because they buried climate in it, it didn=E2=80=99t satisfy climate=
 activists. Climate change may be a key issue 100 years from now, where peo=
ple are asking, Who did what, when? And we could say Biden did more for cli=
mate change than anybody else, by the money he put into that Inflation Redu=
ction Act, yet he gets no credit for it.

But the central problem of Biden=E2=80=99s presidency, and why he didn=E2=
=80=99t get
reelected, is they only had one view of it. Which was, You may not like eve=
rything I do, but the alternative is Donald Trump. That was their strategy.=
 It=E2=80=99s smarter, in my view, to always be optimistic in America. Trum=
p is an aberration from that; he marketeers division and fear. Biden=E2=80=
=99s not going to beat Trump on that ground. Sometimes, Biden reminded me o=
f L.B.J.; he did great legislation, but there was no visual component, ther=
e was no feel.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

How much can Trump unwind of Biden=E2=80=99s legacy?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Right after the inauguration, you=E2=80=99ll see Donald Trump sign 100 exec=
utive orders. That doesn=E2=80=99t mean they=E2=80=99re all going to stick.=
 Some will get booted to the courts, and there will be a lot that=E2=80=99s=
 going to get through=E2=80=A6 I think Trump better tune out the
Bannons of the world; get off a revenge tour; don=E2=80=99t target the pres=
s; sue organizations, like he did with ABC, but don=E2=80=99t target indivi=
duals. Trump=E2=80=99s going to have to watch that his cabinet nominees, if=
 they get confirmed, aren=E2=80=99t exceeding their legal mandate and losin=
g public support.

=C2=A0

Could Biden be seen more favorably if Trump=E2=80=99s second term is consid=
ered disastrous?

=C2=A0

I don=E2=80=99t wish for that in any way, shape, or form. We don=E2=80=99t =
want to see the president fail. But if Trump does fail, or the country star=
ts going into a recession, or worse things happen, there may be people sayi=
ng, God, we miss Biden. That could happen. But only time will tell. Trump i=
sn=E2=80=99t just trying to roll back Bidenism and undo all that climate mo=
ney and undo his executive orders; Trump would like to go all the way
back through Nixon. What brings Elon Musk, Trump, and many others together =
is money, and the federal government regulating everything. They want to cr=
eate a deregulatory federal government wherever they can.

