RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwM=
zI4NDd9/b03756bb02772f023a950da2d26f54f37768c4d13a13be11dd07afdef258bb6d" s=
tyle=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">called</a> for somebody t=
o primary Roy, and he can=E2=80=99t play the same card
twice. Roy=E2=80=99s district is <em>super </em>Trumpy=E2=80=94a rare patch=
 of deep red near Austin, where the Texas Republican political class of ope=
ratives and Hill Country state representatives are concentrated. As such, t=
here=E2=80=99s an ample supply of potential opponents=E2=80=94every wannabe=
 Republican congressmember in the greater Austin metropolitan region ran fo=
r the seat when Roy first did in 2018.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But Roy de=
feated
<em>17 other Republicans</em> in that race. He=E2=80=99s got a killer team =
on speed dial that includes several of the Austin-based strategists who plo=
tted <strong>Ted Cruz</strong>=E2=80=99s upset victory over the establishme=
nt in 2012. And again, he already incurred Trump=E2=80=99s wrath for loudly=
